      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e\u003e services don\u0027t properly remove_interface, but they don\u0027t destroy objects unless application ends, so that\u0027s no problem\n\n\u003e ? Every application I know of uses `remove_interface()`. Can you give examples that don\u0027t?\n\nI literally picked one of the matches for `add_interface()` at random and found example first try: https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-u-boot-env-mgr/blob/master/src/u-boot-env-mgr.cpp\n\nIt doesn\u0027t prove anything though. Just confirmed the hunch. I suspect it\u0027s okay, as interface is removed when the bus is destroyed.\n\n\u003e\u003e they do it \"old way\", because it\u0027s what majority of the code uses\n\n\u003e New code also seems to do it the \"old\" way, so that doesn\u0027t really track for me.\n\nSure, perhaps no adoption comes from the fact, that the new API is just not known. I can see lot of destructors defined only for the sole purpose of calling `remove_interface()` bunch of times. In my experience, necessity of defining destructor just to free up resources, is not welcome with greatest enthusiasm. It\u0027s just yet another boilerplate code and source of errors I wish i didn\u0027t have to write.\n\nAll in all - I\u0027m not gatekeeping anything. I suspect this API had it\u0027s profits and merit, and limited adoption doesn\u0027t mean it\u0027s bad. Limited adoption makes it easier to drop it though. If it comes in your way I understand your sentiment.\n\nIf end goal is to make `remove_interface()` obsolete, I won\u0027t mind how it\u0027s achieved, as this is step in the right direction.",
      "parentUuid": "4742be34_fb6f98b0",
      "revId": "571fac705017a1cfa468d1cbc97c8ddb8c0672ee",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    }
